I have been making this every year since it first appeareed in Bon Appetit back in the early 90s (as I recall). It is always a big hit in our family and for company. Most people are used to brisket, roasted and smothered in onions. But this adds a fresh zip to it, without being too way out. I often add more cranberry sauce than the recipe calls for. It only enhanced the flavor. Adding some brown sugar to the sauce also is great.

Rating: 3
This is my new brisket recipe, and I've been making brisket for years. for the basic recipe I used 1 12-oz beer and one whole can (can, not cup) of whole berry cranberry sauce and 1/2 cup ketchup, then multiplied the whole thing by 1.5 to have more sauce, which was needed. I also used two large Spanish onions. 1 t salt, 1 t pepper. Don't forego browning the onions, it only takes 20 minutes and adds a lot of flavor. I cooked my brisket 3.5 hours, at the recommended 3 hours it wasn't soft enough. I had also added one package baby carrots to the cooking from the beginning. After removing the fat (when cold) I pureed all the sauce, carrots included. It was good and thick, and the sweetness aspect was subtle. No flour needed, or wanted. If you want more sweetness, add a T or two of brown sugar, as recommended below. I served it with mashed potatoes, though potato kugel or pancakes would be great as well. I also served a cold green bean salad. Wine was a Toad Hollow Zinfandel, excellent.

Rating: 4
What a terrific recipe and so simple! I added a little hot sauce to give it some zip. I cooked it at 350 for 1 hour and then 300 for 3 hours. When the meat was ready, I cooled it on a plate and then thickened the sauce with a little flour & water and returned it to the oven for 20 minutes. I will definitely use this recipe again. MK

